{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \SJ, top of your \SJ-T-9 sequence — safe and solid against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Final exam, board one. You are in 4\S needing ten tricks. Count first: six solid trumps, and the minors offer little — the defense has diamond tricks coming and the club honors in dummy face two small ones. Nine on top at best. Study each suit and find the tenth trick, and decide what has to be true for your plan to work.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \SJ; win and draw the trumps. The tenth trick lives in hearts: your \HA-Q sits after East. Cross to dummy in clubs or trumps and lead a LOW heart toward your hand — when East plays low, insert the queen. It holds. The ace follows, and with six trumps, two hearts, and the club pair set up, ten tricks are home while the defense takes its diamonds.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The tool was the SIMPLE FINESSE — lesson one of this family: lead toward the honor you hope will win, and let the defender in front of it commit first. The heart queen was your whole margin, and it scored because East's king sat where the finesse could trap it. One down, nine to go.}
