[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D7, top of your worthless six-card suit — nothing else is safer against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S needing ten tricks. The trump suit will behave, and dummy's clubs are ready — but count again and the hand still wants THREE heart tricks from your \HA-Q-J-8 opposite three small. The king is out and rates to be guarded. One question decides this board: how many times must hearts be led, and from which side?

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The defense takes its diamonds early. Win, and cash the trump ace — West's KING drops singleton, a gift to bank. Now the heart project: cross to dummy and lead low, finessing the JACK — it holds. Back to dummy again, finesse the QUEEN — it holds too. Now the ACE, and East's king, stripped of both guards, falls under it. Three heart tricks, no loser, and ten tricks with the clubs standing by.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The repeated finesse again — the exam gives you the same tool twice to see whether you recognize it in new clothes. East's king had two guards, so two hooks were the entry fee, and dummy's minor-suit cards paid the transportation. Once more: a finesse you may repeat is a suit you must keep entries for.}
