[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H9, top of your small hearts — the passive choice against a slam when nothing else appeals.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 6\C missing the trump ace — so eleven of the remaining twelve tricks must be yours the moment it is gone. Count: five trump tricks once the ace is out, three hearts after that lead, three diamonds. Eleven. The twelfth hides in the spade suit — your \SA-Q-J facing dummy's singleton 8. The exam question: how do you conjure a trick from A-Q-J when you cannot afford to LOSE the lead even once more?

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West's \H9 rides to your king. Knock out the trump ace at once; win the return. Now spades: cash the ACE, then lead the QUEEN-JACK through West — when West covers with the king, dummy RUFFS it away, and your remaining honor is the twelfth trick, no lead ever surrendered. That is the whole slam: the spade king could never win a trick sitting in front of your run.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The ruffing finesse at the slam table — the one finesse that risks nothing, which is exactly what a contract with a certain loser demands. You could not afford a losing hook, so you chose the hook that cannot lose. Two boards to go.}
