{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C2, a low club from your \CT842 — fourth-best from your longest suit.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] The final board: 7\S, all thirteen tricks required, nothing to spare and nothing to hide behind. After nine boards of hooks and ruffs and repeated finesses, here is the last question this exam will ask you: how many finesses does THIS hand need? Count every suit before you answer.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \C2 into your \CA and dummy's K-Q-9-7. Count to thirteen: six trump tricks, the \HA, your \DK plus dummy's \DA with the long diamonds behind them, and three club honors. Thirteen. On top. Draw trumps, set up the diamonds, cash out — and never so much as glance at a finesse, because every one of them is a chance to hand West a trick that the counting already paid for. Claim the grand.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The answer to the final question was NONE — with thirteen tricks on top, every finesse was pure risk and zero reward. And that is the whole family in one sentence: the finesse is a tool for tricks you have not already got. Count first, listen second, hook only when the count and the auction say you must — and when they do, hook without fear. Exam complete; well played.}
